Performing an aggressive port scan returns the result above. There is one SSH application on port 22, and the rest are HTTP. I will start enumeration with the HTTP application on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this web application. It informs me to use the CLI application on port 5132.


The source-code of this webpage contains the HTML comment above. A GraphQL application runs on the target machine at port 8433, as shown above. However, the username and password is needed.

Port 8433: GraphQL HTTP

Before enumerating this application, I enumerated the application on port 5132. That application asks for a username and OTP which I do not have. Then I decided to enumerate this application. And bingo! The GraphQL application is available on this port as shown above. Using this guide from HackTricks, I enumerated this application further.


Using the payload query={__schema{types{name,fields{name, args{name,description,type{name, kind, ofType{name, kind}}}}}}}, I obtained the schema as shown above. There are interesting names such as listUsers, getOTP, getToken, etc, as shown above. Is this the username & OTP the application on port 5132 requires?


Using the payload query={listUsers}, I obtained two usernames: peter, and jason, as shown above. Is it possible to obtain the OTP of the two users? And I found a working command to obtain the value using a key.


I used query={getOTP(username: "peter")} to obtain the OTP of user peter, as shown above.


And using the same payload, but changing the name to jason, I obtained the OTP of jason as shown above.

Port 5132: Python TCP Application

And now I have the usernames and OTPs, I can enumerate this application further. I used the username peter and OHAgQmR1uYwyyH9F, but I did not receive anything. I send bash reverse shell payloads too, but I had no output. Until, I entered the command help.


I executed help first to see the available commands. There are a few commands as shown above. Executing list shows the messages sent to the user peter. And read can be used to read the different messages. I used the command read 234. Apparently peter is using peter@safe as the MySQL password. I was only able to read this message as this user.

Exploitation


I used the credentials peter:peter@safe against the MySQL application, but I had no luck. However, I sprayed the credentials against the SSH application and gained access! Now I have a foothold on the target machine via SSH as the user peter as shown above.

Privilege Escalation


Running ps -auxw | grep -i "root" shows python3 /opt/depreciated/messaging/messages.py is executed by the user root as shown above.


I can read the content of the messages.py script, but I cannot change it. However, this script is interesting as it is the application on port 5132. The function create_message contains the code above. This function can be abused to read sensitive files from the target machine; for example, the msg.json. All the messages are dumped to that file.


Using nc localhost 5132 I connected to the application on port 5132 from the SSH session on the target machine. Then I used the commands above to read the content of /opt/depreciated/messaging/msg.json.


And bingo. I browsed to /opt/depreciated and obtained the password by reading the content of msg.json as shown above. The password 9>XsS+&=Zn#AS9-@ exists. I tried spraying this password against the user joshua and root and gained access!


Now I have root access on the target machine as shown above.
